    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- 1. GRADIENT NOISE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <details open>
      <summary><span class="num">01</span> What Is Gradient Noise?</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>The problem Perlin was solving</h3>
        <p>
          In 1983, Ken Perlin was working on the movie <em>Tron</em> and needed textures that looked natural — marble, wood grain, clouds. The obvious approach (fill each pixel with a random color) produces static — the "untuned TV" look. That's because each pixel is independent of its neighbors. Nature isn't like that: a cloud is bright here, slightly less bright one inch over, even less bright two inches over. Values change <strong>gradually</strong>.
        </p>

        <p>Perlin needed random numbers that change smoothly. His solution was beautifully simple:</p>

        <h3>The idea: random arrows on a grid</h3>
        <p>
          Imagine a sheet of graph paper. At every intersection point, stick a little arrow pointing in a random direction. That arrow is the <strong>gradient vector</strong> — "gradient" just means "direction of change." It doesn't point toward anything special; it's just a random direction, like spinning a compass needle and seeing where it lands.
        </p>

<pre>
Imagine each "+" is a grid point with a random arrow:

    +→    +↗    +←    +↓

    +↑    +↘    +→    +↗

    +↙    +←    +↑    +→
</pre>

        <p>Now, for any point <em>between</em> the grid intersections (that's where the interesting stuff happens), we:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Find the surrounding grid points</strong> — in 2D, that's 4 corners of the cell you're in</li>
          <li><strong>Measure the offset</strong> — how far are you from each corner? This gives you an offset vector for each corner</li>
          <li><strong>Dot product</strong> — for each corner, take the dot product of its random arrow with your offset from it. This gives a single number: positive if you're roughly in the direction the arrow points, negative if you're opposite, zero if you're perpendicular</li>
          <li><strong>Blend smoothly</strong> — interpolate between the four values using a smooth curve (not a straight line, which would create visible creases at grid edges)</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Real-world analogy:</strong> Imagine four fans at the corners of a room, each pointing a random direction. The airflow you feel at any spot depends on how close you are to each fan and which way it's blowing relative to you. The result: a smooth, swirling air pattern — not random chaos, not a rigid grid. That's gradient noise.
        </div>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> In <code>noise.js</code>, change the gradient table <code>GRAD3</code> to only use axis-aligned vectors like <code>[1,0], [0,1], [-1,0], [0,-1]</code>. You'll see the noise develop a subtle grid-like bias. More gradient directions = more natural-looking results.
        </div>

        <div class="reading">
          <strong>Further reading:</strong>
          <a href="https://mrl.cs.nyu.edu/~perlin/paper445.pdf">Ken Perlin's "Improving Noise" (2002)</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- 2. SIMPLEX NOISE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">02</span> Simplex Noise: Why Triangles Beat Squares</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>The problem with the square grid</h3>
        <p>
          Classic Perlin noise lays out gradient arrows on a <strong>square grid</strong>. To compute noise at any point, you need to check every corner of the square you're inside. In 2D that's 4 corners, but in 3D it's 8 (a cube has 8 corners), in 4D it's 16, and so on — it doubles with each dimension. This gets expensive fast.
        </p>
        <p>
          Plus, squares have a problem: they have very obvious horizontal, vertical, and diagonal axes. No matter how you shuffle the gradients, the noise tends to develop subtle grid-aligned patterns. Your "natural" texture has a faint plaid.
        </p>

        <h3>What is a simplex?</h3>
        <p>
          A <strong>simplex</strong> is the simplest possible shape that can tile (fill) a given space with no gaps. Think of it as the "minimal polygon" for each dimension:
        </p>

<pre>
Think of it like this — what's the simplest shape
you can make from connected dots?

  1D: Connect 2 dots → a line segment  ●———●

  2D: Connect 3 dots → a triangle      ●
                                       / \
                                      ●———●

  3D: Connect 4 dots → a tetrahedron     ●
     (a triangular pyramid)             /|\
                                       ● | ●
                                        \|/
                                         ●
</pre>

        <p>
          The key insight: a simplex in N dimensions has only <strong>N + 1</strong> corners. A triangle (2D simplex) has 3 corners, not 4 like a square. A tetrahedron (3D simplex) has 4, not 8 like a cube. That's a huge savings — and it only gets better in higher dimensions.
        </p>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Real-world analogy:</strong> Imagine tiling a bathroom floor. You could use square tiles (easy to lay out, but the grid lines are very obvious). Or you could use triangular tiles — they cover the same floor with less material at each junction, and the pattern is harder to spot because triangles don't align to obvious axes. That's the simplex advantage: fewer reference points, fewer artifacts.
        </div>

        <h3>The skewing trick</h3>
        <p>
          Finding which triangle you're inside sounds hard — but there's a clever geometric shortcut. You <strong>skew</strong> (stretch/shear) the coordinate system so that the triangular grid transforms into a square grid. Then finding your cell is trivial: just round down to the nearest integer.
        </p>
        <p>
          Once you know the square cell, you figure out which of the two triangles you're in by checking: is your x-offset greater than your y-offset? If yes, you're in the lower-right triangle. If no, upper-left. Then you unskew back to compute the real distances.
        </p>

<pre>
Triangular grid (real space):       After skewing (grid space):

     ●-------●                       ●----●
    / \     / \       skew →          | ╱ |
   /   \   /   \      ───→          | ╱  |
  ●-----●-------●                    ●----●
   \   / \   /
    \ /   \ /                       x &gt; y → lower triangle ╱
     ●-----●                        x &lt; y → upper triangle
</pre>

        <p>The skew factor in the code (<code>F2 ≈ 0.366</code>) is derived from the geometry: <code>F = (√3 - 1) / 2</code>. This exact value ensures equilateral triangles transform cleanly into squares. It's not arbitrary — it's baked into the geometry of how triangles and squares relate.</p>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> In <code>noise.js</code>, change <code>F2</code> to 0.5 or 0.2. The noise will look "stretched" because the triangles are no longer equilateral — you've broken the symmetry.
        </div>

        <div class="reading">
          <strong>Further reading:</strong>
          <a href="https://weber.itn.liu.se/~stegu/simplexnoise/simplexnoise.pdf">Stefan Gustavson, "Simplex noise demystified" (2005)</a> — the clearest walkthrough of the full algorithm
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- 3. OCTAVES / FBM -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">03</span> Octaves: Layering Noise for Realistic Detail</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>One layer of noise is too simple</h3>
        <p>
          A single pass of simplex noise gives you smooth, blobby shapes — like gently rolling hills. But look at a real mountain: it has a broad shape (the overall peak), medium ridges on its slopes, small rocks on those ridges, and tiny grains on those rocks. Detail at <em>every</em> scale.
        </p>
        <p>
          To get that multi-scale detail, we <strong>stack multiple layers of noise</strong>, each one "zoomed in" further. Each layer is called an <strong>octave</strong>.
        </p>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Real-world analogy:</strong> Think of audio. A bass guitar plays low, slow vibrations — that's your first octave (broad shapes). A rhythm guitar adds faster vibrations on top — second octave (medium detail). A shaker adds rapid, quiet clicks — third octave (fine texture). Play them together and you get a rich, complex sound. Fractal noise works the same way but with shapes instead of sound.
        </div>

<pre>
Octave 0 (frequency ×1, amplitude ×1):
  Big, slow waves — the overall shape
  ∿        ∿        ∿        ∿

Octave 1 (frequency ×2, amplitude ×0.5):
  Twice as frequent, half as tall
  ∿  ∿  ∿  ∿  ∿  ∿  ∿  ∿

Octave 2 (frequency ×4, amplitude ×0.25):
  Four times as frequent, quarter height
  ∿∿∿∿∿∿∿∿∿∿∿∿∿∿∿∿

Sum of all three:
  ≈ a natural-looking, detailed landscape
  ∿⌇∿̃∿⌇∿̃∿⌇∿̃∿⌇∿̃
</pre>

        <p>In the code, this is the <code>fractal2D</code> function. Each iteration of the loop is one octave:</p>

<pre>
for each octave:
    value += amplitude × noise(x × frequency, y × frequency)
    frequency *= 2      ← "zoom in" for next layer
    amplitude *= 0.5    ← "quiet down" for next layer
</pre>

        <p>Why "octave"? In music, going up one octave means doubling the frequency. Same here: each noise layer has double the frequency of the previous one.</p>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> In the experiment, set the noise scale slider very low. You'll see the broad, smooth shapes of octave 0. Increase it and the finer octaves become visible as turbulence in the flow.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- 4. LACUNARITY & PERSISTENCE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">04</span> Lacunarity & Persistence: Tuning the Texture</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>Lacunarity — how quickly we zoom in</h3>
        <p>
          The word comes from Latin <em>lacuna</em>, meaning "gap." Lacunarity controls the <strong>frequency multiplier</strong> between octaves — how big the "gap" is between each zoom level.
        </p>

<pre>
lacunarity = 2.0 (default — standard doubling):
  Octave 0: frequency ×1
  Octave 1: frequency ×2
  Octave 2: frequency ×4
  Octave 3: frequency ×8
  → Evenly spaced zoom levels, natural-looking detail

lacunarity = 3.0 (aggressive zoom):
  Octave 0: frequency ×1
  Octave 1: frequency ×3
  Octave 2: frequency ×9
  Octave 3: frequency ×27
  → Jumps to very fine detail fast, skips medium scales

lacunarity = 1.5 (gentle zoom):
  Octave 0: frequency ×1
  Octave 1: frequency ×1.5
  Octave 2: frequency ×2.25
  → Octaves stay close in scale, subtle buildup of detail
</pre>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Real-world analogy:</strong> Lacunarity is like choosing zoom levels on a map. Default (2.0) is like going: country → state → city → neighborhood. High lacunarity (3.0) is like: country → city → block — you skip scales. Low lacunarity (1.5) is like: country → region → state → county — each step is small.
        </div>

        <h3>Persistence — how loud each layer is</h3>
        <p>
          Persistence (also called "gain") controls how much each successive octave <strong>contributes</strong> to the final result. It's the amplitude multiplier.
        </p>

<pre>
persistence = 0.5 (default):
  Octave 0: amplitude 1.0    ████████████████
  Octave 1: amplitude 0.5    ████████
  Octave 2: amplitude 0.25   ████
  Octave 3: amplitude 0.125  ██
  → Fine detail fades away quickly → SMOOTH result

persistence = 0.8 (high — rough):
  Octave 0: amplitude 1.0    ████████████████
  Octave 1: amplitude 0.8    █████████████
  Octave 2: amplitude 0.64   ██████████
  Octave 3: amplitude 0.512  ████████
  → Fine detail is almost as loud as coarse → ROUGH, craggy

persistence = 0.25 (low — very smooth):
  Octave 0: amplitude 1.0    ████████████████
  Octave 1: amplitude 0.25   ████
  Octave 2: amplitude 0.06   █
  Octave 3: amplitude 0.015  (barely visible)
  → Only the big shapes matter → VERY SMOOTH
</pre>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Real-world analogy:</strong> Back to the band: persistence is each instrument's volume. High persistence = every instrument is almost equally loud = a wall of sound (complex, rough). Low persistence = the bass dominates, higher instruments are whisper-quiet = a smooth, simple sound.
        </div>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> You can modify the <code>fractal2D</code> call in the experiment. Change the 4th argument (lacunarity) and 5th argument (persistence). Try persistence = 0.8 with speed = 1 — the flow becomes turbulent. Then try persistence = 0.2 — smooth, laminar rivers.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- 5. VECTOR FIELDS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">05</span> Vector Fields: From Noise to Direction</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>What is a vector field?</h3>
        <p>
          A vector field is just a rule that says: <strong>"at this point in space, the direction is ____."</strong> Think of a weather map showing wind direction at every location. At each point there's an arrow: the wind blows this way, this fast.
        </p>

<pre>
A vector field — an arrow at every point:

  ↗  →  →  ↘  ↓
  ↑  ↗  →  →  ↘
  ↑  ↑  ↗  →  ↓
  ↑  ↑  ↑  ↘  ↓
  ↗  ↑  ↑  ↓  ↙

Drop a leaf in this "wind" and it follows
the arrows — that's what our particles do.
</pre>

        <h3>Noise → angle → direction (3 steps)</h3>
        <p>Our noise function gives us a <strong>number</strong> at each point (like a temperature map: -1 is cold, +1 is hot). But we need a <strong>direction</strong>. Here's the conversion:</p>

<pre>
Step 1: Get a noise value
  noise(x, y) → 0.35   (a number between -1 and 1)

Step 2: Convert to an angle
  angle = 0.35 × 2π = 2.2 radians ≈ 126°

  Why 2π? Because 2π radians = 360° = a full circle.
  This maps the full noise range [-1, 1] to all
  possible directions.

Step 3: Convert angle to a direction vector
  vx = cos(126°) = -0.59  (leftward)
  vy = sin(126°) =  0.81  (upward)

  So a particle at this point moves up-and-left.
</pre>

        <p>Because noise is <em>smooth</em> (nearby points have similar values), nearby points get similar angles, which means similar directions. The result: particles flow in coherent streams, not random jitter.</p>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> Imagine changing the multiplier from <code>2π</code> to <code>π</code> in the code. Now angles only range from -180° to 180° — all particles drift roughly rightward. The flow becomes biased. The full <code>2π</code> ensures every direction is equally possible.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- 6. CURL NOISE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">06</span> Curl Noise: Divergence-Free Vortices</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>The problem: particles clump up</h3>
        <p>
          With a regular noise vector field, some areas act as <strong>sinks</strong> (flow converges inward — particles pile up) and <strong>sources</strong> (flow diverges outward — particles flee). Over time, you get unnatural clumps and empty spots.
        </p>

        <h3>The fix: follow the contour lines</h3>
        <p>
          Think of the noise field as a landscape of hills and valleys. The <strong>gradient</strong> at any point is the "steepest uphill" direction — like a ball rolling uphill. If particles followed the gradient, they'd all pile up at the hilltops.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Curl noise rotates the gradient by 90°.</strong> Instead of going uphill, particles walk along the hillside — following the <strong>contour lines</strong> (the lines of equal elevation on a topographic map). No particle ever goes uphill or downhill, so they never pile up or spread out. The flow is <strong>divergence-free</strong>.
        </p>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Real-world analogy:</strong> Imagine water on a smooth hillside. Gravity pulls it downhill (that's the gradient). But if the water had no friction and couldn't speed up, it would flow along the hillside at constant elevation — following the contour lines. That's curl noise. And around a hilltop, the contour lines form a loop — so particles orbit the peak in a vortex!
        </div>

<pre>
Noise landscape (bird's eye view, numbers = height):

      0.2   0.5   0.8
      0.3   0.9   0.7     ← "hilltop" at 0.9
      0.1   0.4   0.3

Gradient at center: points toward 0.9 (uphill)
      → ↑ (uphill)

Curl (rotate 90°): follows contour around the hill
      → ← (circles the hilltop!)
</pre>

        <h3>The math in 4 lines</h3>
<pre>
1. Compute gradient (how fast noise changes in x and y):
   ∂n/∂x ≈ (noise(x+tiny, y) - noise(x-tiny, y)) / (2 × tiny)
   ∂n/∂y ≈ (noise(x, y+tiny) - noise(x, y-tiny)) / (2 × tiny)

2. Rotate 90° to get curl:
   curl_x =  ∂n/∂y       (y-change becomes x-direction)
   curl_y = -∂n/∂x       (negated x-change becomes y-direction)
</pre>

        <p>That's it. The 90° rotation is what makes the magic — it turns a "flow toward hilltops" field into a "flow around hilltops" field.</p>

        <p>The <code>curl</code> slider in the experiment blends between the regular field (curl = 0) and pure curl noise (curl = 1). At intermediate values, you get a mix of streaming flow and vortices.</p>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> Set curl to 1.0 and reduce particles to 500. Watch individual particles orbit the noise peaks in tight loops. Then set curl to 0 — particles stream in rivers and clump at convergence points. The difference is dramatic.
        </div>

        <div class="reading">
          <strong>Further reading:</strong>
          <a href="https://www.cs.ubc.ca/~rbridson/docs/bridson-siggraph2007-curlnoise.pdf">Robert Bridson, "Curl-noise for procedural fluid flow" (SIGGRAPH 2007)</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- 7. ALPHA DECAY & INK MODE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">07</span> Alpha Decay & Ink Mode</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>Why particles fade</h3>
        <p>
          Two things create the trailing effect:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Frame fade:</strong> Each frame, a nearly-transparent dark rectangle is drawn over the entire canvas. This slowly dims everything. After ~25 frames, old strokes are faint. After ~50, essentially gone.</li>
          <li><strong>Particle age:</strong> Each particle has a lifespan. As it ages, its opacity decreases linearly from 1 (fully visible) to 0 (invisible), at which point it "dies" and respawns at a random location.</li>
        </ol>

<pre>
Particle age → opacity:

  Born:    ●●●●● (alpha = 1.0, fully opaque)
  Young:   ●●●○○ (alpha = 0.67)
  Old:     ●○○○○ (alpha = 0.33, fading)
  Dead:    ○○○○○ (alpha = 0, respawns elsewhere)
</pre>

        <p>Together, these create a natural-looking dissipation — like smoke dispersing or ink drying.</p>

        <h3>Ink mode: what it removes</h3>
        <p>
          Ink mode simply <strong>removes the frame fade layer</strong>. Nothing gets erased. Every stroke persists forever, accumulating like ink on paper. Over minutes, the complete structure of the flow field becomes visible — every stream, every vortex, every convergence point is rendered as dense overlapping strokes.
        </p>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> Enable ink mode, choose the "ink" palette, and let it run for 60 seconds. The result looks like a hand-drawn map of invisible currents.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- EXPERIMENT 002 — BOHEMIAN EIGENVALUES -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->

    <h2 style="font-size: 14px; color: #6a8cff; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; margin: 32px 0 16px; padding-top: 24px; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06);">Experiment 002: Bohemian Eigenvalues</h2>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">08</span> What Is an Eigenvalue?</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>The geometric picture</h3>
        <p>
          A matrix transforms space — it stretches, rotates, shears, or reflects vectors. Most vectors come out pointing in a completely new direction. But some special vectors only get <strong>scaled</strong> (longer, shorter, or flipped). These are the <strong>eigenvectors</strong>, and the scale factor is the <strong>eigenvalue</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If A·v = λ·v, then v is an eigenvector and λ is its eigenvalue. The matrix does nothing to this direction except scale it by λ.
        </p>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Real-world analogy:</strong> Imagine stretching a rubber sheet unevenly. Most arrows drawn on the sheet change direction as the sheet deforms. But some arrows — the ones aligned with the stretch directions — stay pointing the same way, just getting longer or shorter. Those are the eigenvectors. How much they stretch is the eigenvalue.
        </div>

        <h3>The characteristic polynomial</h3>
        <p>To find eigenvalues, we solve det(A - λI) = 0. For a 2×2 matrix this gives a quadratic; for 3×3, a cubic. The roots are the eigenvalues.</p>

<pre>
2×2 matrix:  | a  b |
             | c  d |

Characteristic equation: λ² - (a+d)·λ + (ad-bc) = 0
                              ─────        ──────
                              trace      determinant

Apply the quadratic formula:
  λ = (trace ± √(trace² - 4·det)) / 2
</pre>

        <h3>Why eigenvalues can be complex</h3>
        <p>
          Consider a 90° rotation matrix: <code>[[0,-1],[1,0]]</code>. No real vector survives this — everything gets turned. There's no real λ. But complex eigenvalues exist: λ = i and λ = -i.
        </p>
        <p>
          Complex eigenvalues encode rotation. And they always come in <strong>conjugate pairs</strong> (a+bi and a-bi) for real matrices — this is why every Bohemian plot is symmetric across the real axis.
        </p>

        <div class="reading">
          <strong>Further reading:</strong>
          <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PFDu9oVAE1g">3Blue1Brown, "Eigenvectors and eigenvalues"</a> — the best visual introduction
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">09</span> The Complex Plane</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>
          The complex plane maps every complex number a + bi to a 2D point: real part → horizontal, imaginary part → vertical.
        </p>

<pre>
        Im
        ↑
   2i   ·
        |     ● (1 + 1.5i)
   1i   ·
        |
  ──────┼──────→ Re
        |
  -1i   ·
        |     ● (1 - 1.5i)  ← conjugate pair!
  -2i   ·
</pre>

        <p>
          The <strong>argument</strong> (angle from positive real axis) encodes rotation direction. The <strong>modulus</strong> (distance from origin) encodes scale. In the experiment, "color by argument" maps the angle to a hue on the color wheel, revealing rotational structure in the eigenvalue distribution.
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">10</span> Bohemian Matrices & Why the Patterns Exist</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>What "Bohemian" means</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Bo</strong>unded <strong>He</strong>ight <strong>M</strong>atrix of <strong>I</strong>ntegers <strong>an</strong>d their properties. Pick a small set of integers (like {-1, 0, 1}), a matrix size, and enumerate <em>every possible matrix</em>. Compute all eigenvalues and scatter-plot them on the complex plane.
        </p>
        <p>
          For 3×3 with {-1, 0, 1}: 3⁹ = 19,683 matrices × 3 eigenvalues each = 59,049 points. The result isn't noise — it's an intricate fractal-like constellation.
        </p>

        <h3>Where the structure comes from</h3>
        <p>The patterns arise from algebraic constraints:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>The characteristic polynomial has <strong>integer coefficients</strong> bounded by the entry set</li>
          <li>Only finitely many distinct polynomials exist → finitely many root configurations</li>
          <li>Roots of polynomials with small integer coefficients cluster in highly structured ways (this connects to number theory)</li>
          <li><strong>Real-axis symmetry</strong>: complex roots come in conjugate pairs</li>
          <li><strong>Void regions</strong>: some areas of the complex plane are algebraically impossible — no polynomial from the family has roots there</li>
          <li><strong>Fractal boundaries</strong>: the edges where eigenvalue density transitions are infinitely detailed</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> Start with 2×2 {0,1} — only 16 matrices, very sparse. Then switch to 3×3 {-1,0,1} and watch the constellation explode into structure. Then try {-2,-1,0,1,2} — the patterns become even denser and more intricate (warning: 5⁹ = ~2M matrices, it takes a moment).
        </div>

        <div class="reading">
          <strong>Further reading:</strong>
          <a href="http://www.bohemianmatrices.com/">bohemianmatrices.com</a> — the definitive gallery and database
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">11</span> Solving the Cubic: Depressed Cubic Method</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>The 3×3 eigenvalue problem requires solving a cubic. The classical approach:</p>

        <h3>Step 1: Get the characteristic polynomial</h3>
        <p>λ³ - p·λ² + q·λ - r = 0, where p = trace, q = sum of 2×2 cofactors, r = determinant.</p>

        <h3>Step 2: Depress the cubic</h3>
        <p>Substitute λ = t + p/3 to eliminate the λ² term: t³ + mt + n = 0. This is the "depressed" form — one fewer term to deal with.</p>

        <h3>Step 3: Classify by discriminant</h3>
<pre>
Δ = -(4m³ + 27n²)

Δ &gt; 0 → three distinct real roots
       Use the TRIGONOMETRIC method:
       t_k = 2√(-m/3) · cos(θ/3 - 2πk/3)
       for k = 0, 1, 2

Δ &lt; 0 → one real root + two complex conjugates
       Use CARDANO'S formula:
       t = ∛(-n/2 + √disc) + ∛(-n/2 - √disc)
       Then solve the remaining quadratic.
</pre>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Why the trigonometric method?</strong> When all three roots are real, Cardano's formula paradoxically involves complex intermediate values (the <em>casus irreducibilis</em>). The trig method avoids this by recognizing that three real roots of a depressed cubic can be expressed as cosines at equally-spaced angles — a beautiful connection between algebra and geometry.
        </div>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> Read through <code>eigen.js</code> — every step of the solver is commented with the mathematical reasoning. Follow along with a specific 3×3 matrix and verify the eigenvalues match.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- EXPERIMENT 003: REACTION-DIFFUSION -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <h2 style="font-size: 14px; color: #6a8cff; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; margin: 32px 0 16px; padding-top: 24px; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06);">Experiment 003: Reaction-Diffusion</h2>

    <details open>
      <summary><span class="num">11</span> The Gray-Scott Model</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>Two chemicals, A (substrate) and B (catalyst), react and diffuse on a 2D grid:</p>
        <pre>∂A/∂t = Da · ∇²A  -  A·B²  +  f·(1 - A)
∂B/∂t = Db · ∇²B  +  A·B²  -  (k + f)·B</pre>
        <p><strong>Da · ∇²A</strong> — Diffusion of A. The Laplacian ∇² measures how much A at a cell deviates from its neighbors. Concentration flows from high to low, like dye in water.</p>
        <p><strong>A · B²</strong> — Autocatalytic reaction. B catalyzes its own production (B² is the key — positive feedback). This consumes A and produces B.</p>
        <p><strong>f · (1 - A)</strong> — Feed. Fresh A is continuously supplied at rate f. Acts like a nutrient drip.</p>
        <p><strong>(k + f) · B</strong> — Kill. B decays at rate k and is diluted by incoming feed.</p>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Analogy:</strong> Think of A as grass and B as fire. Fire consumes grass (A·B²), grass regrows (feed), fire dies out on its own (kill). The pattern depends on how fast grass regrows vs how fast fire spreads.
        </div>

        <p>The critical asymmetry: Da = 1.0, Db = 0.5. A diffuses twice as fast as B. Without this difference, no patterns form.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">12</span> Turing Instability — Why Patterns Self-Organize</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>In 1952, Alan Turing published "The Chemical Basis of Morphogenesis," proposing that biological patterns — zebra stripes, leopard spots, the arrangement of fingers — could arise from chemistry alone, with no blueprint.</p>
        <p>The key insight: <strong>diffusion-driven instability</strong>. Normally diffusion smooths things out. But when a fast-diffusing inhibitor interacts with a slow-diffusing activator, diffusion can <em>amplify</em> perturbations:</p>
        <pre>1. A tiny excess of B appears at some point
2. B reacts with local A, consuming it  (A·B² reaction)
3. A diffuses back in quickly  (Da &gt; Db)
4. But B stays concentrated  (it diffuses slowly)
5. The incoming A feeds B's autocatalytic growth
6. A-depleted zone around B prevents new clusters nearby
7. Result: regularly spaced B clusters</pre>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Analogy:</strong> Imagine a city where restaurants (B) consume customers (A). Customers travel fast (cars), restaurants don't move. A new restaurant attracts customers from far away, depleting nearby areas. This "moat" of depleted customers prevents another restaurant from surviving too close — creating naturally spaced clusters.
        </div>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> Start with the "spots" preset and watch individual dots split into two — this is the self-replication mechanism. Then switch to "maze" and watch the spots elongate into stripes that fill the domain.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">13</span> The f/k Parameter Space</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>The Gray-Scott model's behavior is exquisitely sensitive to f (feed) and k (kill). Small changes cross <strong>bifurcations</strong> — critical boundaries between qualitatively different patterns.</p>
        <table>
          <tr><th>Pattern</th><th>f</th><th>k</th><th>Description</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Spots</td><td>0.037</td><td>0.060</td><td>Isolated dots that split and self-replicate</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Maze</td><td>0.029</td><td>0.057</td><td>Labyrinthine stripes filling the domain</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Worms</td><td>0.054</td><td>0.063</td><td>Short, wriggling filaments</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Holes</td><td>0.039</td><td>0.058</td><td>B fills space; A survives in scattered holes</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Coral</td><td>0.059</td><td>0.063</td><td>Branching, coral-like growth fronts</td></tr>
        </table>
        <p>Why such sensitivity? Near the bifurcation boundary, tiny shifts in f or k determine whether B spots split, merge, elongate into stripes, or die. Karl Pearson mapped the full parameter space in 1993, identifying at least 12 distinct pattern types.</p>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> Start at "spots" (f=0.037, k=0.060) and slowly increase k using the slider. Watch the spots thin, then struggle, then vanish entirely. You're crossing the bifurcation.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">14</span> The Laplacian and Discrete Approximation</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>The Laplacian ∇²u measures how much u at a point deviates from its local average:</p>
        <pre>∇²u &gt; 0 → local minimum (valley) → concentration flows IN
∇²u &lt; 0 → local maximum (hill)   → concentration flows OUT
∇²u = 0 → matches neighbors      → no net flow</pre>
        <p>On a discrete grid, we approximate it with a 9-point weighted stencil:</p>
        <pre>     0.05  0.2  0.05
     0.2   -1   0.2
     0.05  0.2  0.05</pre>
        <p>The weights sum to zero (0.05×4 + 0.2×4 - 1 = 0). This is required: a uniform field must have ∇² = 0.</p>
        <p>Cardinal neighbors (weight 0.2) contribute more than diagonals (0.05) because they're closer. This produces smoother, more isotropic diffusion than a simpler 4-point cross stencil.</p>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Analogy:</strong> The Laplacian at each cell asks: "Am I hotter or cooler than my neighbors?" If hotter (local max), heat flows out. If cooler (local min), heat flows in. Over time, everything equalizes — that's pure diffusion. The reaction terms fight this smoothing, creating pattern.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- EXPERIMENT 004: STRANGE ATTRACTORS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <h2 style="font-size: 14px; color: #6a8cff; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; margin: 32px 0 16px; padding-top: 24px; border-top: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06);">Experiment 004: Strange Attractors</h2>

    <details open>
      <summary><span class="num">15</span> Dynamical Systems and Phase Space</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>A <strong>dynamical system</strong> is any system whose state evolves over time according to a fixed rule. The rule can be a differential equation (continuous time, like Lorenz) or an iterated map (discrete time, like Clifford).</p>
        <p><strong>Phase space</strong> is the set of all possible states. For a 2D system it's a plane; for 3D it's a volume. A trajectory in phase space shows the system's entire history as a single curve.</p>
        <p>An <strong>attractor</strong> is a set in phase space that nearby trajectories converge toward — the system's long-term behavior. A <strong>fixed point</strong> (pendulum at rest), <strong>limit cycle</strong> (metronome), or <strong>strange attractor</strong> (chaos) are all attractors.</p>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Analogy:</strong> Phase space is like a landscape. Attractors are the valleys — wherever you start on the hillside, you eventually roll down into one. A strange attractor is a valley with infinitely complex terrain: you keep rolling but never reach the bottom, tracing a path that never repeats.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">16</span> What Makes an Attractor "Strange"</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>Two properties define "strange":</p>
        <p><strong>1. Fractal dimension.</strong> The attractor has non-integer dimension. The Lorenz attractor is ≈ 2.06 — more than a curve (1D) but less than a surface (2D). Zoom in and you see infinitely many thin sheets folded over each other, self-similar at every scale.</p>
        <p><strong>2. Sensitive dependence on initial conditions.</strong> Two points starting arbitrarily close diverge exponentially fast — the "butterfly effect." The system is perfectly deterministic, but tiny measurement errors grow so fast that long-term prediction becomes impossible.</p>
        <pre>Two nearby trajectories:

Time 0:    ●● (start close)
Time 10:   ●      ● (diverging)
Time 20:   ●                ● (completely different)

Yet both stay on the same attractor forever.</pre>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> Pick the Lorenz attractor and nudge σ by 0.01. The shape looks similar, but if you could track individual trajectories, they'd be completely different after a few seconds.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">17</span> The Lorenz Attractor and the Weather</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>In 1963, meteorologist Edward Lorenz was running a simplified weather model — three coupled ODEs describing atmospheric convection:</p>
        <pre>dx/dt = σ(y - x)          σ = Prandtl number
dy/dt = x(ρ - z) - y      ρ = Rayleigh number
dz/dt = xy - βz            β = geometry factor</pre>
        <p>He re-entered initial conditions rounded from 6 decimal places to 3. The result diverged completely — a difference of 0.000127 grew into a totally different weather pattern. This was the first concrete demonstration of sensitive dependence.</p>
        <p>The classic parameters (σ=10, ρ=28, β=8/3) produce the iconic butterfly shape: two lobes that the trajectory jumps between unpredictably. The x-z projection reveals this structure.</p>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Analogy:</strong> Imagine a ball on a figure-8 shaped track with a bump at the crossing. Each time it reaches the crossing, tiny differences in speed determine which loop it takes next. The sequence of choices (left, right, left, left, right...) never repeats and is essentially unpredictable.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">18</span> Iterated Map Attractors</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>Not all dynamical systems use differential equations. <strong>Iterated maps</strong> apply a function repeatedly — the Clifford and de Jong attractors are 2D maps with four parameters each:</p>
        <pre>Clifford:  x' = sin(a·y) + c·cos(a·x)
           y' = sin(b·x) + d·cos(b·y)

de Jong:   x' = sin(a·y) - cos(b·x)
           y' = sin(c·x) - cos(d·y)</pre>
        <p>Since sin and cos are bounded to [-1, 1], these maps always produce bounded output — no divergence risk. The four parameters control the frequency and phase of sinusoidal distortions, creating swirling, feathery, or flame-like structures.</p>

        <div class="try-it">
          <strong>Try it:</strong> Click "randomize" repeatedly on the Clifford attractor. Each random parameter set creates a completely different shape — some swooping and organic, others tight and geometric. The variety from just four numbers is remarkable.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><span class="num">19</span> Density Rendering and Histogram Equalization</summary>
      <div class="section-body">
        <p>We render attractors by iterating millions of points and counting pixel visits. But raw hit counts are extremely skewed:</p>
        <pre>Most pixels:   0–1 hits    (outer wisps)
Some pixels:   10–100      (main structure)
A few pixels:  1000+       (dense core)</pre>
        <p>Linear brightness mapping (count/max) makes 99% of pixels nearly black. <strong>Log scaling</strong> compresses the dynamic range:</p>
        <pre>brightness = log(1 + count) / log(1 + max)

count = 0     → 0       (black)
count = 1     → 0.15    (faintly visible)
count = 100   → 0.50    (visible)
count = max   → 1.0     (bright)</pre>
        <p>The logarithm lifts low values and compresses high values, revealing both delicate outer filaments and the dense core simultaneously.</p>

        <div class="analogy">
          <strong>Analogy:</strong> It's like HDR photography. A raw photo of the night sky is either black (stars invisible) or blown out (bright stars as white blobs). HDR compresses the range so you see faint nebulae and bright stars in the same image.
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>

